@node Installation
                          ==================
                          =                =
                          =  Installation  =
                          =                =
                          ==================


     Drag the Installer-icon from the EarTrainer-directory on the disk
to the drawer or volume to  which  you  wish the program to be copied.
Double-click on the Icon  and  the  program  and  this  manual will be
copied. No new directory will  be  created.
@endnode

@node Purpose
                            =============
                            =           =
                            =  Purpose  =
                            =           =
                            =============


     When I was preparing for my examination to enter the jazz section
of the music conservatory of Brussels, I  realized that I had a lot of
difficulties to recognize  intervals.  A  friend  of  mine,  who  is a
qualified music teacher, proposed to help me.
     After a few lesson I made  some  progress, but not really enough.
This was because he only could  spare  one  day  a  week for me and to
advance quickly you should practice  every  day.  I  tried to play the
intervals on my keyboard to  memorize  them,  but what I really needed
was someone (or something) that could test me randomly every day.
Then I got the idea to write this program.
     You are able to choose which  intervals, roots and octaves should
be used for the test. The computer keeps track of every right or wrong
answer. The next test this  knowledge  will  be  used  to ask you more
questions about the intervals on which you made the most mistakes.
     First I finished a version roughly  (version  1.0). In this way I
could already start  practising  myself  and  I  must  say that within
several days I made a huge progress. I used my spare time to start all
over again  and  to  write  a  very  powerful  version  that  could be
customised to suit everybody's needs.

     So if you need to obtain very  quickly a relative pitch, use this
program. You will see that it really does a magnificent job.
@endnode

