     To keep the registration as simple  as  possible I wrote a little
registration program. Please use  this  because  then you're sure that
everything is correct.
     First  type  your  personal  data  in  the  corresponding  string
gadgets. Then you have to indicate if this is an initial registration,
a first update or a further update. If you wish to obtain the C source
code you should select the checkbox.  You  will  see the price of your
order and the number of  disks  to  include  to the right. Active your
printer and press on the 'print registration form'-button and the form
will be printed. Fill  in  a  Eurocheque  with  the correct amount and
write my address on an  envelope.  Then send everything (Disks, Cheque
and Form) to me. I will send  you  the program within three days after
the receival of your order.


@endnode

@node Usage
                             ===========
                             =         =
                             =  Usage  =
                             =         =
                             ===========


     The entire program can  be  customised  to suit your preferences.
The changes are saved in a  configuration  file that is located in the
S: directory. If this file is not  present at the start of the program
the eartrainer will begin in  the standard configuration. Don't forget
to unprotect our floppy-disks  if  you  don't  have  a hard-disk but a
floppy-disk system.

                            @{" Windows Menu " link Windows}
                          @{" Preferences Menu " link Preferences}
                            @{" Project Menu " link Project}
                           @{" Key Short-cuts " link Key}

                                @{" Tips " link Tips}

@endnode

@node Windows
                          ==================
                          =                =
                          =  Windows Menu  =
                          =                =
                          ==================


     Every window that you open by  choosing  it  from the menu can be
changed in position.  This  movement  will  be  remembered  and can be
saved. In this way you can  set  up  the  display the way you like it.
When you open the windows for the  first  time they will appear like I
prefer them for a screen of 640x512 pixels. There is a new gadget left
to the depth gadget in every  window.  When you press this, the window
will reset its position.
     When windows are being covered by  other ones you can always look
at the menu to see which  ones  are  active. They are indicated by the
checkmark. The windows can be closed   by   using the menu once again,
by pressing on the close gadget or by pressing the Escape-key when the
window is active.

               Windows
                    |
                    |-> @{" About window " link About}
                    |-> @{" Intervals window " link Intervals}
                    |-> @{" Notation window " link Notation}
                    |-> @{" Octaves window " link Octaves}
                    |-> @{" Piano window " link Piano}
                    |-> @{" Report window " link Report}
                    |-> @{" Roots window " link Roots}
                    |-> @{" Status window " link Status}
@endnode

@node About
                          ==================
                          =                =
                          =  About window  =
                          =                =
                          ==================


     This should be  very  obvious.  The  window  displays  some short
information about the  program.  It's  the  only  active  one when the
program is started up for the  first  time.  I guess this will also be
only time that it will be active.  You  will probably want to close it
for future use of the program.
@endnode

@node Intervals
                        ======================
                        =                    =
                        =  Intervals window  =
                        =                    =
                        ======================


     This  window  displays  all  the   intervals.  Each  interval  is
presented by a checkmark gadget and by a button gadget:

     ---------------------
     |V|      Unison     |
     ---------------------

     When the  checkmark  is  present,  the  computer  will  use  this
interval during the quiz. This  allows  you  to work systematically by
learning groups of intervals and by combining them afterwards.
     E.g.: First you activate the  minor  and  the major third for the
quiz. Once you obtain frequently a 100% correct score, you can move on
by selecting only the prefect fourth  and  the perfect fifth. When you
can also recognize them perfectly, combine the two groups by selecting
the four of them together. And so on ...

     The button gadget with the  name  of  the  interval written on it
contains three functions depending on the situation:
     1. You're not participating in a quiz.
     2. You're thinking about which interval the computer is playing.
     3. You've answered to a question but haven't pushed continue yet.

     This are the different functions.
     1. The computer will play the selected interval. He will randomly
choose amongst the checked roots and the checked octaves. This is very
useful to study an interval before taking  a quiz. You're forced to do
it starting from different roots.
     2. The selected interval will by considered as your answer to the
question. The computer will compare it with his generated interval and
tell you if your answer is  correct  or  wrong. You will also see that
the status window will adapt to your reply.
     3. The computer will  play  the  selected  interval with the same
root and octave as the one he generated for the last question. This is
very useful when your answer  was  wrong  or when you're still unsure.
You can listen to different intervals  to  check why you interpret the
generated one wrongly.

     There are two other buttons,  the  ALL  and the NONE button. When
you  press  them  you  will  respectively  select  or  clear  all  the
intervals.
@endnode

@node Notation
                         =====================
                         =                   =
                         =  Notation window  =
                         =                   =
                         =====================


     This window displays the  generated  intervals  in standard staff
notation. You  can  trigger  its  way  of  working  in  the  intervals
preferences.
@endnode

@node Octaves
                         ====================
                         =                  =
                         =  Octaves window  =
                         =                  =
                         ====================


     This  window  displays  all  the   octaves.  Each  octave  is
presented by a checkmark gadget and by a button gadget:

     --------------
     |V| Octave 1 |
     --------------

     When the  checkmark  is  present,  the  computer  will  use  this
octave during the quiz.

     You can only use  the  gadgets  in  this  window  when you're not
participating in a quiz. When you press the button gadget the computer
will randomly choose between  the  checked  intervals  and the checked
roots. He will  however  use  the  octave  you  selected  to  play the
interval.

     There are two other buttons,  the  ALL  and the NONE button. When
you press them you will respectively select or clear all the octaves.
@endnode

@node Piano
                          ==================
                          =                =
                          =  Piano window  =
                          =                =
                          ==================


     This window  displays  a  piano  keyboard.  You  can  activate or
deactivate  it  in  the   Intervals   Preferences  window.  When  it's
activated, you can see every note played on the piano keyboard.
     When you click on a key  of  the piano the computer will randomly
choose amongst the checked intervals. He will however use the key  you
pressed as the root of the interval  that will be played. You can only
press on the keys of the lower three octaves.
@endnode

@node Report
                          ===================
                          =                 =
                          =  Report window  =
                          =                 =
                          ===================


     This window displays what goes on  when  you take a quiz. You see
the number of the question that you  have to answer, the evaluation of
your answer (correct or  wrong)  and  when  the  quiz is finished, the
number of questions you've answered correctly.

     There are three gadgets in this window:
     1. Start quiz/Stop quiz
     2. Continue
     3. Again

     And there functions are:
     1. Start or stop the quiz.
     2. You should press this  interval  when  its enabled to continue
the quiz. When  the  Continue  gadget  is  enabled,  you  can press an
interval button to compare different intervals with the generated one.
     3. When you press Again, you will hear the last interval that the
computer generated.
@endnode

@node Roots
                          ==================
                          =                =
                          =  Roots window  =
                          =                =
                          ==================


     This window displays all the roots.  Each  root is presented by a
checkmark gadget and by a button gadget:

     --------------
     |V|   B#/C   |
     --------------

     When the  checkmark  is  present,  the  computer  will  use  this
root during the quiz.

     You can only use  the  gadgets  in  this  window  when you're not
participating in a quiz. When you press the button gadget the computer
will randomly choose amongst  the  checked  intervals  and the checked
octaves. He will  however  use  the  root  you  selected  to  play the
interval.

     There are two other buttons,  the  ALL  and the NONE button. When
you press them you will respectively select or clear all the roots.
@endnode

@node Status
                          ===================
                          =                 =
                          =  Status window  =
                          =                 =
                          ===================


     When you do a quiz, the computer  keeps track of every correct or
wrong answer. You can see this  record  in  this window. Even when the
window is closed, the computer continues to record every answer.
     The status file is saved  at  exit.  In the preferences menu this
can be disabled. I  must  ask  you  to  use  this option very sparsely
because  'The  EarTrainer'  needs  the   status   file  to  adapt  his
questioning to your weaknesses.
     You can clear, print or save the  status file at wish by pressing
the appropriate gadgets in the  title-bar.  When  you clear the status
file, this only happens to  the   work-duplicate  that  resides in the
memory. This change will be saved  automatically  at exit, except when
you have disabled this option.
@endnode

@node Preferences
                        ======================
                        =                    =
                        =  Preferences menu  =
                        =                    =
                        ======================


     When you select one of these  menu-items, a window will appear to
enable you to change the preferences.  Except  for the Display and the
Set save path  windows,  you  can  leave  the  windows  open and still
continue to work. Every window  has  Apply,  Apply & Close and Restore
buttons. The Apply button activates  your  changes.  The Apply & Close
does the same but  closes  the  window  afterwards. The Restore button
restores the window preferences to the previous state.

               Preferences
                    |
                    |-----> @{" Display " link DisplayPrefs}
                    |-----> @{" Intervals " link IntervalsPrefs}
                    |-----> @{" Midi " link MidiPrefs}
                    |-----> @{" Print " link PrintPrefs}
                    |-----> @{" Quiz " link QuizPrefs}
                    |-----> @{" Sound " link SoundPrefs}
                    |-----> Configuration
                    |              |
                    |              |-----> @{" Reset " link ResetConfig}
                    |              |-----> @{" Save " link SaveConfig}
                    |              |-----> @{" Save at exit " link ExitConfig}
                    |-----> Status
                              |
                              |---> @{" Clear " link ClearStatus}
                              |---> @{" Print " link PrintStatus}
                              |---> @{" Save " link SaveStatus}
                              |---> @{" Set save path " link PathStatus}
                              |---> @{" Save at exit " link ExitStatus}
@endnode

@node DisplayPrefs
                         ==================
                         =                =
                         =  DisplayPrefs  =
                         =                =
                         ==================


     A requester appears with  a  list  of  available screenmodes. The
default is Pal Hires. There  two  integer  gadgets where you can write
the size of the screen. The width  can  vary  from 640 to 1280 and the
height from 256  to  1024.  If  enter  lower  or  higher  numbers, the
computer will set them to nearest limit.
     If you haven't got a multiscan or a doublescan monitor, you can't
use DblPal, DblNtsc, Multiscan, ...  modes.  I  can only advice you to
save some money for  a  while  and  buy  a  the  microvitec  1438 or a
commodore 1942. Once you get  to  work frequently in screen dimensions
of 640x512 you'll see how  spacy  and  professional your Amiga monitor
output looks.
     For those persisting 1084, ... users it is possible to choose for
example Pal Hires as screen  mode  and  to  have a screen dimension of
640x512. The lower half  of  the  screen  will  be  invisible but will
appear when you move with  the  mouse  in  it (Autoscroll screen). Use
this to put the status window  in.  It  allows  you quick access to it
without opening and closing it all the time on the other windows.
     When you change a screen when for example from 640x512 to 640x256
and you still have an opened Status  window at position 0x361, it will
be moved so that the lower edge falls exactly on the lowest accessible
point of the screen.
@endnode

@node IntervalsPrefs
                        ====================
                        =                  =
                        =  IntervalsPrefs  =
                        =                  =
                        ====================


               ======================================
               =  +---Interval type----+ +-Piano-+  =
               =  | _                  | |       |  =
               =  ||_|Simultaneously   | | O Off |  =
               =  ||_|Succesively      | | O On  |  =
               =  ||_|Succ. & Reversed | +-------+  =
               =  +--------------------+            =
               =                                    =
               =      +--Display notes--+           =
               =      |                 |           =
               =      | O Off           |           =
               =      | O Before answer |           =
               =      | O After answer  |           =
               =      +-----------------+           =
               ======================================


     You can change the way of  playing the interval. Either the notes
are played simultaneously (together), successively (first the root and
then the second note)  or  successively  &  reversed (first the second
note and then the root).  Each  type  can be selected individually and
when several are  chosen  the  computer  will  choose randomly amongst
them. The  notation  window  will  adapt  its  way  of  displaying the
intervals.
     The intervals can be displayed in  the notation window at several
times : never, before the computer  waits  or after the computer waits
for your answer. When it's being  displayed before the waiting you can
use this program also to train your  ability to read intervals. If the
displaying occurs after your answer  it  can  be  used  as a method of
checking.
     You can trigger the functioning of  the piano keyboard. When it's
on, you will see the intervals being played on the keyboard.
@endnode

